		<div class="l-text b-typo">
			<div><p>I&nbsp;heard about this discussion (yes, from Edvantis, in&nbsp;which&nbsp;I have no&nbsp;position or&nbsp;interest) and wanted to&nbsp;share some thoughts that might be&nbsp;helpful. For my&nbsp;background, I’m Mark Kapij, an&nbsp;American entrepreneur of&nbsp;Ukrainian descent, and after starting my&nbsp;first company in&nbsp;the US&nbsp;I&nbsp;spent two years living in&nbsp;Ukraine to&nbsp;help start new companies in&nbsp;the early 90’s. I&nbsp;founded SoftServe by&nbsp;recruiting the current owners (trivia quiz...anyone know which two founders wrote the first busines plan for SoftServe?), providing them advice, capital, space and equipment to&nbsp;start their company- because starting good new companies in&nbsp;Ukraine was the goal. I&nbsp;and Myroslav&nbsp;M (of&nbsp;Advantis) brought SoftServe a&nbsp;majority of&nbsp;their clients and revenue over the years. Recent events seem dissappointing though. I&nbsp;know the company and management quite well, and again worked with the company a&nbsp;few years ago developing the firm’s Boston office.</p>

<p>Having heard about this discussion of&nbsp;reputation and firms, and mostly since I&nbsp;do care to&nbsp;see a&nbsp;diverse vibrant group of&nbsp;software companies grow and emerge in&nbsp;L’viv, I&nbsp;would like to&nbsp;just add a&nbsp;few points. I&nbsp;am assuming the audience here is&nbsp;the software developer community trying to&nbsp;make sense of&nbsp;what companies are better and worse as&nbsp;employers, and of&nbsp;course the character of&nbsp;each firm’s management is&nbsp;part of&nbsp;that understanding. </p>

<p>Some things that might help as&nbsp;you come to&nbsp;your conclusions:</p>

<ul><li>I&nbsp;can share my&nbsp;opinion that&nbsp;I find it&nbsp;hard to&nbsp;believe the Edavantis team stole SoftServe clients, given that&nbsp;I believe Myroslav is&nbsp;one of&nbsp;the most knowledeabe executives in&nbsp;offshore outsourcing and marketing&nbsp;I ever met in&nbsp;Ukraine (having worked/advised about a&nbsp;half dozen firms in&nbsp;Ukraine, and recently several in&nbsp;India). He&nbsp;was far more capable of&nbsp;working with clients and finding and developing them than anyone else in&nbsp;top management at&nbsp;SoftServe (who in&nbsp;fact have a&nbsp;poor record on&nbsp;this), hence it&nbsp;seems SoftServe has much more to&nbsp;gain by&nbsp;discrediting him than he&nbsp;does by&nbsp;ever “stealing clients”. He&nbsp;is&nbsp;one of&nbsp;the few in&nbsp;that company that really knows how to&nbsp;develop clients.

</li><li>I’d add in&nbsp;fact these accusations sound very much like my&nbsp;own experience not too long ago, where in&nbsp;fact SoftServe failed to&nbsp;uphold terms of&nbsp;our agreement, inventing accusations in&nbsp;the process. I&nbsp;am not surprised that they could have done a&nbsp;similar thing with Myroslav, it&nbsp;is&nbsp;the same story replayed. I&nbsp;find it&nbsp;more likely to&nbsp;believe they found a&nbsp;way not to&nbsp;compensate him, than anything else given this similarity. Sadly Ukraine doesn’t yet have the legal and court infrastructure to&nbsp;keep things clear, and at&nbsp;the same time some can take advantage of&nbsp;this.

</li><li>I&nbsp;know for years the larger firms in&nbsp;L’viv colluded (fixed salaries, limited competitive hiring) to&nbsp;prevent fair salary competition, which of&nbsp;course in&nbsp;the&nbsp;US is&nbsp;illegal, but not so&nbsp;in&nbsp;Ukraine (or&nbsp;is&nbsp;it&nbsp;also not legal, just not enforced?). It&nbsp;happens often when a&nbsp;small group of&nbsp;large firms control most of&nbsp;the jobs. It&nbsp;is&nbsp;easy to&nbsp;see how this is&nbsp;also a&nbsp;motivation for all kinds of&nbsp;behavior and again, this sort&nbsp;of (what&nbsp;I think is&nbsp;false) discrediting of&nbsp;really promising good new companies should not even be&nbsp;suprising to&nbsp;see and hear for any of&nbsp;you. In&nbsp;the end for the developer community a&nbsp;large diverse growing set of&nbsp;companies is&nbsp;the best thing for all of&nbsp;you! Find the jobs that really interest and challenge you, and make your own conclusions by&nbsp;asking questions.

</li><li>On&nbsp;my&nbsp;last visit to&nbsp;Lviv I&nbsp;was pleased to&nbsp;learn that there were now something like 70&nbsp;software firms, mainly outsourcing, which is&nbsp;terrific. Trust&nbsp;me, for a&nbsp;firm like SoftServe whose main strategy was controlling the talent (you!), these must be&nbsp;worrisome times. Keep an&nbsp;eye out for even more interesting behavior!

</li></ul>Now is&nbsp;likely one of&nbsp;the best times to&nbsp;start new businesses in&nbsp;software in&nbsp;years, and it&nbsp;is&nbsp;very great to&nbsp;hear about all the activity in&nbsp;Lviv. I&nbsp;encourage all of&nbsp;you to&nbsp;keep exploring the opportunities, go&nbsp;start your own companies, the more the better.

<p>-Mark<br>Boston, MA<br><a href="mailto:mkapij@gmail.com">mkapij@gmail.com</a> </p>

<p>p.s. My&nbsp;apologies, I&nbsp;read and speak fluently in&nbsp;Ukrainian, but typing is&nbsp;not so&nbsp;easy. For the entrepreneurs, feel free to&nbsp;write, am&nbsp;happy to&nbsp;help when I&nbsp;can.</p></div>
		</div>

				<a class="review-link" href="https://jobs.dou.ua/companies/edvantis-software/reviews/29185/">
					Ссылка
				</a>

			<div class="sup-users">
					<span></span>
			</div>

